I just try to pick something in the video,
something that I have spoken, something that

00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:49.270
I have shown, and picturise it in an interesting
manner.

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:50.570
That’s all.

00:05:50.570 --> 00:05:51.990
A little creative liberty there.

00:05:51.990 --> 00:05:57.790
So, if you look at this video, for example,
there is this story of a guy who has a chip

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:00.910
embedded near his heart, and that chip contains
a code…

00:06:00.910 --> 00:06:06.850
And that was the reason for this thumbnail.

00:06:06.850 --> 00:06:13.680
Shine and Glow — the poet or poetess that
that person is, shared with me something really

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:15.190
interesting about beauty.

00:06:15.190 --> 00:06:23.860
She referred to the natural fact of the watermelon
not hanging down from up in a tree as something

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:24.860
truly beautiful!

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:25.860
Very interesting!

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:34.730
Blender Forever helped us all by saying, “Oh,
here are the upcoming numbers and the corresponding

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:35.730
dates.”

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:38.840
Q375–8th February, Q376, Q377, and so on.

00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:46.680
That’s when I realised that probably some
of you missed what the whole game was about.

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:48.590
Why is it seemingly random?

00:06:48.590 --> 00:06:52.460
When will the next Quotidian be released?

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:55.021
Is it not happening everyday like in 2021?

00:06:55.021 --> 00:07:00.350
Answers to such questions can be had if you
watch Quotidian — 369.

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:02.950
I had explained it quite extensively there.

00:07:02.950 --> 00:07:08.990
I have explained there about when we are meeting
next.

00:07:08.990 --> 00:07:13.970
And you will understand that it is revolving
around the concept of Pi.

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:14.970
That 22/7…

00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:15.970
Or the irrational 3.1415…

00:07:15.970 --> 00:07:21.889
The dates come based on that special sequence
in the value of Pi.

00:07:21.889 --> 00:07:28.180
So, you will learn that the next meeting would
be on the 21st of March, and the one after

00:07:28.180 --> 00:07:31.500
that on the 23rd of March.

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:35.950
Sumitra asked me — I am still searching
for a leader..

00:07:35.950 --> 00:07:38.380
I have seen many BOSSes.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:42.270
But, I am still looking for that leader.

00:07:42.270 --> 00:07:45.660
I want to turn that question back at her.

00:07:45.660 --> 00:07:50.680
I want to ask her — Have you been a good
follower?

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:52.340
You keep asking for a leader..

00:07:52.340 --> 00:07:53.860
But, have you been a good follower first?

00:07:53.860 --> 00:08:03.139
I think it was Vivekananda, Swami Vivekananda…
who said: “He who wants to lead or command,

00:08:03.139 --> 00:08:05.020
must know how to obey”.

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:11.190
I am thinking of publishing a Quotidian about
this very topic.

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:22.340
What are the qualities that represent that
ideal second-in-command, that ideal person

00:08:22.340 --> 00:08:29.620
who serves a leader, that ideal follower,
let’s see..

00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:34.090
Arunkumar Jothilal said: I went around googling
for it, and that’s when I learned much.

00:08:34.090 --> 00:08:39.389
I looked at the etymology for the word and
noticed that the original meaning comes from

00:08:39.389 --> 00:08:40.630
Old English.

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:41.630
Yes!

00:08:41.630 --> 00:08:44.829
This is an amazing habit that you’ve got
going there.

00:08:44.829 --> 00:08:46.070
It is a great hobby.

00:08:46.070 --> 00:08:47.110
Very interesting stuff…

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:51.921
When you look deeper into inscrutable matters,
inner meanings, and original etymology, it

00:08:51.921 --> 00:08:54.760
will suddenly plop on your lap unexpectedly!

00:08:54.760 --> 00:09:07.170
Also, one more thing you can try is “The
same word, what was in French, what was in

00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:08.170
Spanish”.

00:09:08.170 --> 00:09:10.720
That would be very interesting too.

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:11.740
Try it!

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:14.089
We saw that Need For Speed.

00:09:14.089 --> 00:09:15.529
Should we go fast?

00:09:15.529 --> 00:09:17.339
Or… should we go slow?

00:09:17.339 --> 00:09:19.140
And that’s when this happened.

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:22.330
We were trying to login to Facebook.

00:09:22.330 --> 00:09:26.650
And, Facebook showed us this beautiful prompt.

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:32.010
It talked about how your account could be
secured, introduced a few steps, and had a

00:09:32.010 --> 00:09:37.020
progress bar that slowly went, “Checking
your app passwords”.

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:43.350
Don’t we know about how powerful the Facebook
servers are?

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:47.890
Don’t I know that there are not too many
App passwords to be checked?

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:53.470
But, if it rushes too fast, we wouldn’t
know what Facebook is doing..!

00:09:53.470 --> 00:09:59.550
And, if it does it very fast, we will wonder
did it even do it at all?!

00:09:59.550 --> 00:10:07.690
For THAT reason, consciously, artificially,
on purpose, it runs a slow progress bar, “See?

00:10:07.690 --> 00:10:11.920
I am checking your passwords carefully, do
you get that?”

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:13.890
it seems to say.

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:16.730
That was really really beautiful!

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:22.980
A friend pointed out to me about that guy
from Silicon Valley..

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:26.300
The guy who squats in front of his manager,
“Hmm, give me the stuff I asked you for!”.

00:10:26.300 --> 00:10:28.000
He referred to this persistent character in
the Raja Harishchandra story, by name Nakshatreyan,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.300
and wondered if he was the same kind of guy.

00:10:31.300 --> 00:10:32.300
Yes.

00:10:32.300 --> 00:10:33.300
Correct!

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:35.870
It is Nakshatreyan!

00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:43.899
He also told me that the number of Shlokas
that Lord Ganesha struggled to understand

00:10:43.899 --> 00:10:44.899
the meaning of…

00:10:44.899 --> 00:10:48.500
Seems there is an exact count of that — 8192!

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:57.310
Those were the number of shlokas that were
unusually hard so that Vyasa had time to cook

00:10:57.310 --> 00:10:59.360
up the next one.

00:10:59.360 --> 00:11:00.460
Smart!

